article.headline: Miami has won nine of 10
article.linkText: Heat, with frantic finish, playing for home court
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- Dwyane Wade wants to be on the court with the game on the line, an attitude his coach appreciates. Only one thing, though. "If he wants to be in those situations, he has to play defense," Miami Heat coach Stan Van Gundy said. "We want him on the court, but this isn't football. He has to play defense." Wade made a go-ahead runner over Bob Sura to cap a frantic comeback in the final minute, and the Miami Heat held off the Atlanta Hawks 100-97 Wednesday night. The victory propelled the Heat into a tie with the Milwaukee Bucks and the New Orleans Hornets for fourth in the East. The Bucks lost to the Indiana Pacers 111-78 and the Hornets fell to the Utah Jazz 89-76. Eddie Jones had 23 points and Lamar Odom added 21 before fouling out for Miami, which won for the ninth time in the past 10 games. Wade finished with 10, then explained his defensive woes. "You got four or five guys who can shoot real good, that's hard to guard," Wade said with a shrug. Stephen Jackson scored 29 points and Jason Terry had 23 for the Hawks, who lost their second straight after only their second two-game winning streak of the season. They scored only one point in the final 3:30. Earlier in the day, the nine-man ownership group that bought the Hawks and the NHL's Atlanta Thrashers officially took control of the teams. Six of the new owners sat courtside and were introduced to the crowd during a stoppage in the first half, along with new vice president of basketball Dominique Wilkins. They met briefly with the team before the game. "They want it to get better," Sura said. "They seem really enthusiastic about owning a team. It's going to be good for the city of Atlanta." Atlanta took its biggest lead on a dunk by Chris Crawford with 3:30 left to make it 96-88, but Odom responded with a three-point play. The Hawks turned the ball over three times in their next four possessions, and Jackson missed a 3-pointer in the other one. Jones swished a 3 to bring the Heat within two, and Odom tied it with a leaner over rookie Boris Diaw. "We put ourselves in the hole," Odom said. "A lot of people don't realize that Atlanta's had a tough year, but that's a tough offensive team. They spread us out pretty well." After Jackson made one of two free throws to give Atlanta its final lead, Jones missed a 3-pointer. But teammate Brian Grant pushed Crawford out of the way for the rebound, and Wade eventually ended up with the ball. He drove on Sura and made his shot with 39.6 left, give Miami its first lead of the fourth quarter. The Hawks had another turnover on the next possession, and after Rafer Alston made two three throws, Terry and Crawford missed 3-pointers that would have tied it. "The only thing I'll say is we were very resilient, which we have been lately," Van Gundy said. "Their energy and effort was far superior to ours." With reserves Wesley Person and Zeljko Rebraca out with injuries, the Hawks' 10-deep roster included three players who originally signed 10-day contracts. That list included starting center Jason Collier. It showed, too. The five players reserves combined to miss all 10 of their shots and didn't score a single point. At one point, someone seated behind the bench pleaded for coach Terry Stotts to send in "Hawk for a Day" Brian Saripkin, a fan who won a radio contest and got to dress with the team. "It's unusual," Stotts said of his playing rotation. "It is unusual, but it is what it is."

Game notes
Sura finished with 14 points and 14 rebounds. ... The Heat activated C Loren Woods and put C Wang Zhi-Zhi (turf toe) on the injured list before the game. They still were without F Malik Allen, who sprained his knee Monday night against the Chicago Bulls. ... As expected, the loudest cheers of the night were for Wilkins when he was introduced. He sat with his brother, Gerald, for much of the game. Gerald's son, Damien Wilkins, a player at the University of Georgia, sat nearby.
